{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nExisting stores must learn they are behind the registry without hot-path cost — Rails\n`CheckPending` for a School-B registry: compare the applied-set to the registry ids, nudge on\nwrite activity, cheaply, rate-limited, never breaking a write.\n\n## What\nWS1 landed the registry as `rebar._store.ensures` and exports, on that module: `REGISTRY_IDS`\n(the frozen id tuple), `registry_ids() -> frozenset[str]`, `applied_ids(tracker) -> set[str]`\n(parses `.ensure-applied`, degrading absent/garbage/non-list → empty set), and `APPLIED_MARKER`\n(`.ensure-applied`). WS2 adds the write-path pending-nudge to THAT module (no new module) plus the\n`EnsureConfig` config section.\n\n**Pending computation (compute-once, per process).** Add `maybe_emit_pending_hint(tracker)` to\n`rebar._store.ensures`. It computes `pending = registry_ids() - applied_ids(tracker)` and caches\nthe resulting SET of pending ids in a module-level dict keyed by the canonical tracker path — so\n`.ensure-applied` is read AT MOST ONCE per store per process (a converged store caches the empty\nset and every later write is O(1), zero further reads). The cache holds the id SET (not a bare\nboolean) precisely so the emitted hint can NAME the pending units. When `.ensure-applied` is\nabsent/unreadable/garbage, `applied_ids` returns the empty set so `pending` = all registry ids (a\npre-feature store is genuinely behind) — the hint fires, but the rate-limit bounds it to ≤1 per\ninterval so there is no per-write spam.\n\n**Where it hooks (single choke point).** Call `maybe_emit_pending_hint` best-effort at the end of\n`event_append.write_and_push` (after a successful commit+push). Covered via `write_and_push`:\n`_seam.append_event` (comment/tag/edit/link/set_*/sign) and the `composer` create/edit/revert\npath (which call `append_event` → `write_and_push`). We hook ONLY `write_and_push`, NOT\n`_seam.append_event` (which itself calls `write_and_push`), so there is no double-firing.\nBest-effort, NOT universal — the ACCEPTED GAP set commits inline (raw `git commit`, NOT through\n`write_and_push`) and is intentionally NOT hooked: `claim` (`txn.claim_core` + `push_after_commit`),\n`transition`/close (`txn.transition_core` + `push_after_commit`), `compact.py`, `delete.py`, plus\nthe ensure units themselves and `fsck --repair` batches. A rate-limited nudge is not a correctness\nmechanism, and these mutators still surface pending state on the NEXT covered write. Pure reads\n(list/show/…) never touch the hook.\n\n**Emission + rate-limit.** Emit a single WARNING that names the pending unit ids and points to\n`rebar fsck --repair` (the EXISTING heal verb — WS3 folds the ensure-sweep into it), but only when\n`pending` is non-empty AND the last-hinted timestamp in `.ensure-hinted` is older than the\nconfigured interval. Reading `.ensure-hinted` is symmetric with `.ensure-applied`: an absent OR\nunparseable/garbage `.ensure-hinted` is treated as \"never hinted\" (`last = None`), so the hint\nfires (and then writes a fresh timestamp) rather than being silently suppressed. On a decision to\nhint, rewrite `.ensure-hinted` with the current time via `fsutil.atomic_write`\n(temp-in-same-dir + os.replace — same helper WS1 uses for `.ensure-applied`). `.ensure-hinted`\n(WS2-owned, git-ignored: ADD to `_GITIGNORE` at init.py:38-48) holds a single timestamp. A fresh\nauto-init'd worktree already has a current `.ensure-applied` (WS1 wrote it), so `pending` is empty\nand it NEVER hints.\n\n**Config.** Add an `EnsureConfig` section to `_config_schema.py` (`ensure.hint_interval_secs`=86400,\n`ensure.hint_enabled`=true) with the full scaffolding: the `@dataclass EnsureConfig`, an entry in\n`_SECTION_CLASSES`, coercers in `_SECTIONS` (`_as_int(minimum=0)` / `_as_bool`), an `ensure` field\non `Config`, and a re-export from `config.py`. Adding the section to `_SECTIONS` is automatically\npicked up by `config._env_signature()` (which iterates `_SECTIONS`) so the env layer + cache key\nwork with no further edits. The hint reads these via `config.load_config(...).ensure`.\n\n**Env-var documentation decision.** The env overrides are auto-derived by `config._canonical_env_name`\nas `REBAR_ENSURE_HINT_INTERVAL_SECS` / `REBAR_ENSURE_HINT_ENABLED` — no per-key entry needed. These\nnames are built DYNAMICALLY (never appear as a literal `os.environ[\"…\"]`), and `docs/env-vars.md` is\nGENERATED by `scripts/gen_env_registry.py`, whose AST scanner only captures literal `os.environ`/\n`os.getenv` reads. So the ensure env vars are (a) NOT captured by the drift gate and (b) `docs/env-vars.md`\nmust NOT be hand-edited (the gate would regenerate it and fail on the diff). The `[ensure]` section and\nits two env overrides are documented in `docs/config.md` instead (WS4 also covers them in\n`docs/migrations.md`). No generated file is edited.\n\n**Fail-silent.** `maybe_emit_pending_hint` swallows ALL of its own exceptions — including a lazy-import\nImportError/SyntaxError from `rebar._store.ensures` / `rebar.config` — behind a debug log, so a write\nNEVER fails because of it. There is no import cycle: `event_append` lazy-imports `ensures` inside\n`write_and_push` (module load order unaffected), and `ensures` never imports `event_append`. A rare\ndouble-hint under parallel agents (two processes both past the interval) is accepted.\n\n## Scope\nIn: `maybe_emit_pending_hint` in `rebar._store.ensures` (compute-once pending-set cache, rate-limit via\n`.ensure-hinted` + `fsutil.atomic_write`), the best-effort `write_and_push` hook (lazy import,\nfail-silent), the `.ensure-hinted` `_GITIGNORE` entry, `EnsureConfig` scaffolding, and the `[ensure]`\ndocs in `docs/config.md`. Out: `run_ensures()` + `.ensure-applied` format/write (WS1), `fsck --repair`\nfold + `ensures: N/M` line (WS3), `docs/migrations.md` (WS4), the exhaustive hot-path/idempotency suite (WS5).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `maybe_emit_pending_hint(tracker)` computes `pending = registry_ids() - applied_ids(tracker)` and caches the pending id SET once per process per canonical tracker; a converged store reads `.ensure-applied` at most once and does zero further reads on subsequent writes (verified by test (e): a spy on `applied_ids` shows exactly one read across two hint calls on the same tracker)\n- [ ] `.ensure-hinted` read degrades symmetrically to `.ensure-applied`: an absent or unparseable/garbage marker is treated as \"never hinted\" so the hint fires (not silently suppressed), then a fresh timestamp is written\n- [ ] The hook is called best-effort only from `event_append.write_and_push` (covering `_seam.append_event` leaf writes and the composer create/edit/revert path, which funnel through it); `_seam.append_event` is NOT separately hooked (no double-fire); the accepted-gap inline committers (claim/transition via `txn.*_core`+`push_after_commit`, compact, delete) are NOT hooked and this is documented; pure reads are untouched\n- [ ] The WARNING names the pending unit ids and points to `rebar fsck --repair`, rate-limited via `.ensure-hinted` (written with `fsutil.atomic_write`; added to `_GITIGNORE`) using `ensure.hint_interval_secs` (86400s); suppressible via `ensure.hint_enabled` and its auto-derived env override `REBAR_ENSURE_HINT_ENABLED` (no generated-file edits; `docs/env-vars.md` untouched)\n- [ ] `EnsureConfig` scaffolding complete (`@dataclass EnsureConfig` + `_SECTION_CLASSES['ensure']` + `_SECTIONS['ensure']` coercers + `Config.ensure` + `config.py` re-export); the `[ensure]` section + its two env vars are documented in `docs/config.md`\n- [ ] The hook swallows all its own exceptions incl. lazy-import failures (debug-logged) so a write never fails; there is no import cycle between `event_append` and `rebar._store.ensures`\n- [ ] WS2 owns four concrete tests: (a) a pending store (empty/absent `.ensure-applied`) emits exactly one WARNING naming pending units + `rebar fsck --repair`, and re-emits only after the interval; (b) a fresh auto-init'd worktree (current `.ensure-applied`) emits NO warning; (c) `ensure.hint_enabled=false` suppresses the warning even when pending; (d) fail-silent — when the pending computation raises (e.g. `applied_ids` patched to raise), `maybe_emit_pending_hint` swallows it (no exception propagates) and a real `write_and_push` still commits successfully with the hook installed (covering AC5); (e) read-dedup — a spy/counter on `applied_ids` shows exactly one read across two `maybe_emit_pending_hint` calls on the same tracker (covering the ≤1-read cache claim)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783627740619864001,"uuid":"f64f7d5f-085d-4bf0-bbb3-3d244273d0d6"}